Lead (title):
FDA Adopts Policy to Stretch Monkeypox Vaccine Supplies
The changes mean public-health officials could reach five times as many people with Bavarian Nordic’s Jynneos vaccine
Brief description:
The Food and Drug Administration adopted a new strategy for stretching out monkeypox vaccine doses by allowing for the administration of a smaller dose.

Under the changes, patients will get injections of the vaccine shallowly into the skin, rather than the normal method deeper into the layer of fat under the skin. Each of the injections would be one-fifth of the normal dose.

People will still get two injections, four weeks apart.
